content:
The "Office of National Environmental Technologies Act" aims to improve coordination of research and development across government agencies, private industry, universities, and research centers to provide environmentally safe solutions for national environmental security and competitiveness. SEC. 3. DEFINITIONS.

(1) Administrator - Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency;
(2) Advisory Council - Industry and Academia Advisory Council established by section 5;
(3) Assistant Administrator - Assistant Administrator, Office of National Environmental Technologies, EPA;
(4) Fund - Environmental Advanced Research Projects Revolving Fund established by section 9;
(5) Office - Office of National Environmental Technologies established pursuant to section 4. The Administrator shall establish an Office of National Environmental Technologies within the EPA, headed by an Assistant Administrator. The Office's functions include program definition and management. Staff appointments are allowed, with limitations on confidential or policymaking positions. The Office of National Environmental Technologies coordinates planning, identifies areas needing technical solutions, supports technology development, and facilitates interagency coordination. The Office of National Environmental Technologies coordinates among departments, agencies, and the private sector for exchanging technological information, supporting research and development of advanced technologies, monitoring private industry research, and promoting technological industrial base development in the United States. An interagency advisory committee is established with the Administrator as the chair. The interagency advisory committee, chaired by the Administrator, includes representatives from various government departments such as the Office of Science and Technology Policy, Department of Energy, Department of Commerce, Department of State, Department of Defense, NASA, Department of the Interior, and Department of Agriculture. Their role is to advise and provide information on environmental technologies to the Office. The Industry and Academia Advisory Council is established. The Industry and Academia Advisory Council is established with 9 members appointed by the Administrator, at least 5 from U.S. industry. Members must be eminent in various fields, selected based on distinguished service, and not federal government employees. Recommendations from National Academies, professional societies, and business associations are considered for appointments. The Advisory Council consists of members appointed for 3-year terms, with restrictions on reappointment after serving 2 consecutive terms. Initial members are appointed to staggered terms, and the Council must meet quarterly or upon request by one-third of members. The Advisory Council requires a majority of members without conflicts of interest to form a quorum for meetings. Members must receive at least 15 days notice before a meeting. The Council appoints a chair and vice chair from its members. It reviews and makes recommendations on the Office's policies, organization, budget, and programs within national policy frameworks. The Administrator has general authority as outlined in Section 6. The Administrator, under Section 6, has the authority to enter contracts, use services of other departments, and supervise activities related to patents within the US. The Administrator has the authority to oversee patents, inventions, trademarks, copyrights, and royalty payments related to technologies for environmental restoration and protection. They can appoint advisory committees and transfer technology to the private sector for environmental purposes. SEC. 7. COOPERATIVE AGREEMENTS AND OTHER ARRANGEMENTS. The Administrator may enter into cooperative agreements with various entities to carry out functions of the Office. Federal agencies must cooperate fully with the Administrator to avoid duplication and improve coordination of environmental research. Agreements may include provisions for payments from entities. The Administrator may enter into cooperative agreements with entities for environmental research functions. Payments may be required as a condition for receiving assistance, with the amount credited to the Fund. The Administrator ensures non-duplication and appropriate use of authority. The Administrator may enter into cooperative agreements for environmental research functions, ensuring non-duplication and cost-sharing with the other party. SEC. 8. PROGRAM REQUIREMENTS. The Administrator will establish selection criteria for recipients of contracts, leases, grants, and agreements under this Act within 180 days. Procedures for financial reporting and auditing will be implemented to ensure funds are used appropriately. The Advisory Council's advice will be regularly considered. The Administrator will ensure that the Advisory Council's advice is routinely considered. Research results will be disseminated appropriately. Contracts or awards require merit review for scientific and technical merit. Federal funds must be used for direct costs only. Joint ventures must involve small US businesses for consideration. Section 552 of title 5, United States Code does not apply to confidential information related to businesses or joint ventures receiving funding under this Act. This includes business operations, trade secrets, and intellectual property. The United States is entitled to a share of licensing fees and royalties from businesses or joint ventures funded under this Act. Fees and royalty payments are made to businesses or joint ventures in proportion to the Federal share of costs incurred. Contracts or awards must include provisions for project discontinuance and return of unspent funds if satisfactory progress is not made. Upon joint venture dissolution, the US is entitled to a share of residual assets proportionate to the Federal costs. The Federal share of costs in joint ventures is determined by independent audit. SEC. 9. REVOLVING FUND. Establishment of the "Environmental Advanced Research Projects Revolving Fund" in the Treasury of the United States to provide financial assistance for environmental security needs through loans, grants, and other means to research centers, universities, and entities. Loans made under this fund will bear interest determined by the Secretary of the Treasury. The Secretary of the Treasury determines the interest rate for loans under the Environmental Advanced Research Projects Revolving Fund. Repayments and proceeds are credited to the Fund, which is managed by the Treasury Secretary. Investments are made by the Treasury Secretary for the Fund. The Secretary of the Treasury invests the portion of the Fund not needed for current withdrawals in interest-bearing obligations of the United States. The Administrator must submit an annual report to Congress detailing the Office's activities, future plans, technology usage, and overseas technology transfers. Appropriations of $85,000,000 for 1994, $165,000,000 for 1995, and $250,000,000 for 1996 are authorized, with a limitation of 5% for administrative expenses.
